                        </div>
                      </div>

                      <p id="eip-134">
                        Everyday measurement units are often defined as fractions or multiples of other units. Milk is commonly packaged in containers of 1 gallon (4 quarts), 1 quart (0.25 gallon), and one pint (0.5 quart). This same approach is used with SI units, but these fractions or multiples are always powers of 10. Fractional or multiple SI units are named using a prefix and the name of the base unit. For example, a length of 1000 meters is also called a kilometer because the prefix
                        <em data-effect="italics">kilo</em> means “one thousand,” which in scientific notation is 10
                        <sup>3</sup> (1 kilometer = 1000 m = 10
                        <sup>3</sup> m). The prefixes used and the powers to which 10 are raised are listed in
                        <a
                          class="autogenerated-content"
                          href="#fs-idm81128320"
                        >Table 1.3</a>.
                      </p>

