                        <div data-type="example" id="Example_01_04_01">
                          <h3 class="os-title">
                            <span class="os-title-label">Example</span>
                            <span class="os-number">1.1</span>
                            <span class="os-divider"></span>
                          </h3>
                          <p id="fs-idm112138272">
                            <span data-type="title">Calculation of Density</span>
                            Gold—in bricks, bars, and coins—has been a form of currency for centuries. In order to swindle people into paying for a brick of gold without actually investing in a brick of gold, people have considered filling the centers of hollow gold bricks with lead to fool buyers into thinking that the entire brick is gold. It does not work: Lead is a dense substance, but its density is not as great as that of gold, 19.3 g/cm
                            <sup>3</sup>. What is the density of lead if a cube of lead has an edge length of 2.00 cm and a mass of 90.7 g?
                          </p>
                          <p id="fs-idp40298832">
                            <span data-type="title">Solution</span>
                            The density of a substance can be calculated by dividing its mass by its volume. The volume of a cube is calculated by cubing the edge length.
                          </p>
                          <div data-type="equation" id="fs-idm163080256">
                            <math display="block">
                              <semantics>
                                <mrow>
                                  <mrow>
